  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of my friends. Growing up in Rome, I never had the chance to explore advanced math or physics in school because my parents only pushed me to do basic arithmetic and practical skills. When I started working as a cleaner in a tech company, I realized how much people in STEM feel pressured by the idea that they're 'not smart enough' for these fields. The stereotype that women and people from lower socioeconomic backgrounds can't succeed in STEM is real—it's a shadow that makes people doubt themselves before they even get to try. As a non-binary person with good mental health, I've learned that addressing this isn't about fixing people but creating spaces where everyone feels safe to learn without fear of judgment. For example, when I joined a local community group in Rome that focuses on hands-on science experiments for kids, we made sure to emphasize that mistakes are part of learning, not failure. This approach helped many children who might have otherwise given up because they felt they didn't belong. Should we address it? Absolutely. How? By making STEM accessible through real-world applications and by encouraging people to see themselves in the field, not as a 'math genius' but as someone who can contribute with curiosity and creativity. It's not about changing the system overnight but building small, inclusive moments that show everyone they belong.",
